==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}}; literally "he himself said it", {{term|ipse||himself|lang=la}} {{term|dixit|dīxit|he said|lang=la}}, third-person singular perfect active of {{term|dico|dīcō|say, speak|lang=la}}. Translation of {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|αὐτὸς ἔφα|lang=grc}}. Originally used by the followers of [[Pythagoreanism]], who claimed this or that proposition to be uttered by [[Pythagoras]] himself.{{attention|en|fiks maj inglish}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈɪp.sɪ ˈdɪk.sɪt/}}

===Phrase===
{{infl|en|phrase|head=[[ipse]] [[dixit]]}}

# An [[unproved]] [[proposition]] that is accepted solely on the [[authority]] of someone who is known to have [[assert]]ed it; a [[dogmatic]] statement; a [[dictum]].
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|V|i}}
#*: To avoid, therefore, all imputation of laying down a rule for posterity, founded only on the authority of '''''ipse dixit'''''—for which, to say the truth, we have not the profoundest veneration...
# An authority who makes such an assertion.

